d judgment. At the same time,others have defended passions and emotions as temperingreason and enriching judgment, and there is mountingempirical evidence linking emotions to moral judgment. InPassions and Emotions, a group of prominent scholars inphilosophy, political science, and law explore three clustersof issues: “Passion & Impartiality: Passions & Emotions inMoral Judgment”; “Passion & Motivation: Passions & Emotionsin Democratic Politics”; and “Passion & Dispassion:Passions & Emotions in Legal Interpretation.” This timely,interdisciplinary volume examines many of the theoreticaland practical legal, political, and moral issues raised by suchquestions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmotions. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aPolitical participationxPsychological aspects. 0aPolitical psychology. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBandes, Susan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalhoun, Cheshire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleming, James E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrazer, Michael L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriswold, Charles L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKersch, Ken I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrause, Sharon R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, George E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyler, Bernadette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrinz, Jesse J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanger, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWest, Robin, eco